                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/4590a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Edge</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-07-17T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 17, 1931—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>265. For Mr. Stimson. This afternoon’s news reports from Paris seem to suggest
                    that the French are planning to keep the German delegation at Paris for
                    discussions with them, with the Americans also participating. Of course this
                    would suggest that the French are trying to put off the London conference. The
                    President thinks that under these circumstances you should tell the French that
                    Mr. Mellon and you are planning to go to London Sunday morning. This should
                    indicate to them our opinion that the London meeting should take place as
                    scheduled.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
